sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Potential Raspberry Robin Registry Set Internet Settings ZoneMap
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects registry modifications related to the proxy configuration of the system, potentially associated with the Raspberry Robin malware, as seen in campaigns running in Q1 2024.
Raspberry Robin may alter proxy settings to circumvent security measures, ensuring unhindered connection with Command and Control servers for maintaining control over compromised systems if there are any proxy settings that are blocking connections.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

T1573.description: Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Uses HTTPS for network communication, use the SSL MITM Proxy cookbook for further analysis

T1036.description: Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools.

T1055.description: Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.

T1070.006.description: Adversaries may modify file time attributes to hide new or changes to existing files.
Binary contains a suspicious time stamp

T1548.description: Adversaries may circumvent mechanisms designed to control elevate privileges to gain higher-level permissions.

T1070.description: Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.

T1027.description: Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.
Binary may include packed or crypted data

T1027.002.description: Adversaries may perform software packing or virtual machine software protection to conceal their code.
Binary may include packed or crypted data
PE file has an executable .text section which is very likely to contain packed code (zlib compression ratio < 0.3)

T1059.description: Sample might require command line arguments, analyze it with the command line cookbook
Sample may offer command line options, please run it with the command line option cookbook (it's possible that the command line switches require additional characters like)

T1562.001.description: Creates guard pages, often used to prevent reverse engineering and debugging

T1497.description: May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis
Allocates memory with a write watch (potentially for evading sandboxes)
Checks if the current process is being debugged

T1056.description: Creates a DirectInput object (often for capturing keystrokes)

T1010.description: Sample monitors Window changes (e.g. starting applications), analyze the sample with the simulation cookbook

T1016.description: Checks the online ip address of the machine

T1571.description: Detected TCP or UDP traffic on non-standard ports
